495
00:30:37,921 --> 00:30:41,073
Rym: So, speaking of good and bad people, let's talk about Chili.

496
00:30:41,134 --> 00:30:42,580
Rym: I can't believe we haven't done a show on this.

497
00:30:43,261 --> 00:30:52,820
Scott: Well, so the thing with Chili, the food, right, is that I think because of the culture of the Chili cook-off, right?

498
00:30:53,361 --> 00:30:55,239
Rym: Yeah, which I'm a big fan of.

499
00:30:55,660 --> 00:30:55,760
Scott: Right?

500
00:30:55,901 --> 00:31:01,340
Scott: There's this sort of-- unlike other foods, right, Chili has competition sort of built into it.

501
00:31:01,440 --> 00:31:07,620
Scott: Whereas, I guess barbecue does a little bit, but it's really-- Chili is like the forefront of food that's competing.

502
00:31:07,920 --> 00:31:10,640
Rym: Well, competing not-- There's also pie, pie contests.

503
00:31:10,640 --> 00:31:11,221
Scott: You know what I'd say?

504
00:31:11,281 --> 00:31:20,360
Rym: There's contests for all these things, but Chili has a lot more, like, people will just kind of do a Chili cook-off on their own and sort of self-organize.

505
00:31:20,881 --> 00:31:24,190
Rym: Like, my work had a Chili cook-off recently, just randomly.

506
00:31:24,210 --> 00:31:26,977
Rym: Like, all the engineering teams were like, "Let's make a Chili cook-off.

507
00:31:27,017 --> 00:31:27,399
Rym: Fuck it, let's

508
00:31:27,419 --> 00:31:27,539
Rym: go.".

509
00:31:28,241 --> 00:31:37,058
Scott: Right, you know, the county fair will have contests for pies and things like that, but the Chili cook-off is really the preeminent American food competition.

510
00:31:38,505 --> 00:31:40,560
Rym: Also, Chili is one of my favorite foods.

511
00:31:41,140 --> 00:31:55,280
Scott: Right, and that culture of competition around Chili, I think, results in this particular food being-- giving people very strong opinions about the right way, the wrong way, the better way, the worse way, what makes it good, what makes it bad.

512
00:31:55,621 --> 00:32:03,053
Scott: Like, how to score a Chili, right, on a cont-- I'm unwilling to talk about the true origins of Chili.

513
00:32:03,213 --> 00:32:05,900
Rym: I don't care about the debate of whether or not beans are traditional.

514
00:32:05,940 --> 00:32:15,600
Scott: I think the internet just says it came from, like, you know, working class, you know, Latinx people in Texas or something, right?

515
00:32:16,140 --> 00:32:21,820
Rym: I mean, Wikipedia, in Spanish, the word "Chili" from the Nahatl "Chili" refers to a chili pepper.

516
00:32:22,780 --> 00:32:23,680
Rym: Mm-hmm, yep.

517
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:26,745
Rym: There's the cowboy stuff, beans are not beans, but whatever.

518
00:32:26,805 --> 00:32:34,239
Rym: Really, what we're talking about are braised dishes that involve some combination of chili powders and--.

519
00:32:34,940 --> 00:32:37,424
Rym: And then beyond this, this could be an "or" list, obviously.

520
00:32:37,864 --> 00:32:48,060
Rym: Beans, braised meats, other, like, onions, celeries, tofu's, but usually it's like a chili con carne with braised meat, tomato, and onions and stuff.

521
00:32:48,581 --> 00:33:07,200
Scott: Yeah, I mean, usually, but, yeah, it's just, it's a stew, right, and the stew is usually red and spicy and has a bunch of stuff in it, and it's such a wide variety of different things, meaning, like, this minimal, like, common factor that they all qualify as chili, right?

522
00:33:07,720 --> 00:33:25,180
Scott: It's like, you can get a turkey chili with bean, you can get a vegetable chili, you can get a chili that doesn't even need tomato going on, you can get a chili with just, like, basically ground up, it's basically just your scooping ground up bits of meat that have been spiced and sauced lightly, right, or heavily.

523
00:33:26,561 --> 00:33:30,900
Rym: There are people who are already taking issue in the streaming chat with our inclusion of beans.

524
00:33:31,760 --> 00:33:32,759
Scott: Yep, well, deal with it.

525
00:33:33,140 --> 00:33:39,520
Rym: Yep, because when it comes to chili, I am not a purist at all, and I fucking love almost any kind of chili.

526
00:33:39,801 --> 00:33:40,662
Rym: Yeah, I mean, a

527
00:33:40,702 --> 00:33:56,560
Scott: lot of, like I said, a lot of people have these no true Scotsman arguments of what is chili, what is not chili, and you know what, I don't give a shit, I just care that it is delicious, and if I have to say the word chili to have someone bring that food to me so that I will eat it, then I will say that word, and I do not care.

528
00:33:56,760 --> 00:34:01,440
Rym: Well, the same person is saying that tofu is bad, not because it's vegetarian, that's awesome, but because it's also beans.

529
00:34:04,080 --> 00:34:09,719
Scott: Tofu is beans, that is correct, but it is also delicious, and I would welcome a tofu chili that is tasty.

530
00:34:10,360 --> 00:34:17,960
Rym: But I think the main reason I like chili, my feelings on chili are primarily that the power of chili is that it's real hard to fuck up.

531
00:34:18,100 --> 00:34:21,929
Rym: Even if you suck, you will make an edible, satisfying chili.

532
00:34:21,969 --> 00:34:26,179
Rym: Like, you have to really, really fuck up to make a chili that I wouldn't eat.

533
00:34:26,601 --> 00:34:37,000
Scott: But, if you're good at it, get chili mix at the grocery store, get the cheapest one, buy a meat and follow the instructions, and like, get a can of sauce, and you'll have a chili that is food.

534
00:34:37,400 --> 00:34:41,500
Rym: And even if you mess it up, if you just let it sit long enough simmering, it'll eventually taste good.

535
00:34:42,701 --> 00:34:54,580
Rym: But, at the same time, if you understand the fundamentals of cooking braised dishes, then you don't need a recipe, like, you can just make any kind of chili and it'll always be good, not edible, but like, good.

536
00:34:55,701 --> 00:34:57,224
Rym: Because, there's not that much to it.

537
00:34:58,346 --> 00:35:13,820
Rym: There's a chili recipe I've used for most of my life that basically is just how to make the three stages of preparing a chili, and I know what kinds of ingredients to put in at what part of the chili cooking process, and by following that rubric, I can make chili out of fucking anything.

538
00:35:15,563 --> 00:35:20,680
Scott: Well, I think that's also, right, that wide birth, girth.

539
00:35:20,984 --> 00:35:21,072
Rym: Yup.

540
00:35:22,440 --> 00:35:23,630
Scott: No, birth, as in B-E-R-T-H.

541
00:35:24,900 --> 00:35:26,059
Rym: We ain't talking about Gandalf.

542
00:35:26,761 --> 00:35:28,720
Scott: Yeah, the wide birth of things that could count.

543
00:35:28,740 --> 00:35:31,159
Rym: That is an inside joke from a long time ago.

544
00:35:32,601 --> 00:35:40,840
Scott: The wide birth of things that could count as chili is also what leads towards, you know, back into that, you know, competitive scene.

545
00:35:41,321 --> 00:35:52,240
Scott: Right, because it's like if chili was one specific, like if you have a cheesecake competition, it's like, you can't have that much variety where things are still cheesecake, it's like different toppings, different flavors, how smooth is it, right?

546
00:35:52,882 --> 00:35:56,380
Scott: It's wide, but it's like, it's not chili wide, right?

547
00:35:56,420 --> 00:36:05,060
Scott: You can have chili with different meats, different sauce, different spice, hotter, less hot, bean, no bean, throw some vegetable in there, don't put some vegetable in there.

548
00:36:05,140 --> 00:36:06,840
Rym: I like to use a primarily celery base.

549
00:36:07,120 --> 00:36:09,237
Scott: A looser chili, a thicker chili, right?

550
00:36:09,820 --> 00:36:15,540
Rym: It's very stew adjacent too, but I think the distinction is, chili, all chilis are stews, but not all stews are chilis.

551
00:36:16,960 --> 00:36:28,000
Rym: I feel like the line there is just stew is put a bunch of shit in a pot, chili is put a bunch of shit in a pot, braise parts of it, and use at least some amount of chili peppers.

552
00:36:29,680 --> 00:36:31,239
Scott: Alright, so some of my favorite chilis.

553
00:36:31,643 --> 00:36:32,299
Rym: Stu Leonard's chili?

554
00:36:32,821 --> 00:36:37,260
Scott: Stu Leonard's chili, so if you don't know, this is a grocery store, you may have mentioned it on GeekNights before.

555
00:36:37,823 --> 00:36:41,240
