00:37:57,340 --> 00:37:57,442
Scott: Yep.

581
00:37:58,092 --> 00:37:58,559
Scott: Why wouldn't you?

582
00:37:59,303 --> 00:38:00,629
Rym: And it's just like a solid chicken chili.

583
00:38:00,709 --> 00:38:03,100
Rym: Chicken chili is really underrated chili.

584
00:38:03,240 --> 00:38:03,883
Rym: It's harder to make.

585
00:38:03,943 --> 00:38:08,240
Rym: well because you can kind of burn the chicken if you braise it the wrong way and it'll be kind of tough.

586
00:38:08,240 --> 00:38:16,100
Scott: Well, I think one thing I've learned cooking chicken lately is I've pretty much, you know, it's like I already like dark meat better than white meat.

587
00:38:16,261 --> 00:38:17,440
Scott: That's not new, right?

588
00:38:17,740 --> 00:38:26,360
Scott: But basically now I'm like, I've realized, I've sort of taken that thing I already knew, which is dark meat is better, and just been like, wait a minute, I know dark meat is better.

589
00:38:26,440 --> 00:38:28,199
Scott: I've known that for a super long time.

590
00:38:28,701 --> 00:38:30,025
Scott: Why don't I go all in on that?

591
00:38:30,085 --> 00:38:35,500
Scott: So whenever I make chicken, almost any chicken thing I make, I'm making boneless skinless thighs.

592
00:38:36,200 --> 00:38:38,916
Scott: Or getting boneless thighs and removing the bone, right?

593
00:38:39,920 --> 00:38:42,740
Scott: And just, you know, so if I was going to make a chili, I would just go all thigh.

594
00:38:42,922 --> 00:38:42,989
Scott: Yep.

595
00:38:43,305 --> 00:38:43,480
Scott: Right.

596
00:38:43,640 --> 00:38:49,460
Rym: Because you can make a chili with just like ground like white chicken, but you got to braise, you got to be careful with the braising.

597
00:38:49,560 --> 00:38:56,037
Scott: Like you got to use more oil, you've got to like really- You got to spice that chicken to basically, you know, really season that chicken and keep it juicy.

598
00:38:57,041 --> 00:38:58,925
Rym: And you really got to deglaze.

599
00:38:58,965 --> 00:39:03,716
Rym: Like deglazing is important for like a beef chili, but with a chicken chili, if you don't deglaze, you're like all.

600
00:39:03,736 --> 00:39:05,400
Rym: the flavor is just going to be stuck to your pan.

601
00:39:06,300 --> 00:39:06,876
Scott: Yep, yep, yep.

602
00:39:07,640 --> 00:39:10,166
Rym: But that's, you know, the key to making a good chili.

603
00:39:10,286 --> 00:39:12,090
Rym: for me is the process of like.

604
00:39:12,130 --> 00:39:16,480
Rym: the first thing you have to put into that bowl is you braise whatever meat you're going to use.

605
00:39:16,781 --> 00:39:22,740
Rym: If you're using tofu or something like that, that isn't like a primary meat, you don't put that in right away, you put that in way later.

606
00:39:23,700 --> 00:39:30,640
Scott: You braise the meat- It's not a meat that's going to give off a lot of delicious fat when you braise it down.

607
00:39:30,880 --> 00:39:31,679
Rym: Got to put that oil in there.

608
00:39:31,980 --> 00:39:33,625
Scott: You got to add some oil, right?

609
00:39:33,645 --> 00:39:35,832
Scott: So if you get a tofu, you got to go with sesame oil.

610
00:39:35,872 --> 00:39:38,560
Scott: maybe, go for Asian style chili with the tofu, I don't know.

611
00:39:38,800 --> 00:39:41,060
Rym: Ooh, I've never used sesame oil before.

612
00:39:41,420 --> 00:39:41,823
Scott: Yeah, why not?

613
00:39:41,843 --> 00:39:44,020
Scott: You can make an Asian style, Asian fusion chili.

614
00:39:44,320 --> 00:39:52,460
Rym: What I tend to do is I'll braise either cubed chunks of beef or ground beef and then I'll set it aside and without cleaning out the pot, I'll put in a bunch of oil.

615
00:39:52,901 --> 00:40:02,200
Rym: And usually, as much as I like to make the traditional like just a pile of onions for the base, I actually tend to use primarily celery, like one onion and two hunks of celery, like big hunks.

616
00:40:03,301 --> 00:40:08,620
Rym: And then I just braise that down until it's like unrecognizable mush and the whole pot is covered in fond.

617
00:40:09,140 --> 00:40:10,704
Scott: Yeah, it's a lot like making curry, right?

618
00:40:10,724 --> 00:40:12,548
Scott: It's like I'm making curry from scratch.

619
00:40:12,728 --> 00:40:17,720
Scott: and I think, you know, all the really difference with the curry is that curry is like, okay, I take some onions, right?

620
00:40:18,180 --> 00:40:20,306
Scott: Disintegrate them down into nothing, right?

621
00:40:20,607 --> 00:40:24,158
Scott: Get your braised, you know, boneless, skinless thighs in there, right?

622
00:40:24,298 --> 00:40:24,880
Scott: You know, whatever.

623
00:40:25,360 --> 00:40:32,558
Scott: And the thing with the curry is that you go with water and then you put in, you know, your, what's the word for it?

624
00:40:32,578 --> 00:40:33,320
Scott: The butter flour.

625
00:40:33,902 --> 00:40:35,920
Rym: Oh, the, yeah, I know what you're talking about.

626
00:40:36,420 --> 00:40:40,117
Scott: Yeah, you take butter and flour and you cook them together and you make whatever it is.

627
00:40:40,137 --> 00:40:40,820
Scott: There's a word for it.

628
00:40:40,820 --> 00:40:40,990
Scott: The roux?

629
00:40:41,762 --> 00:40:42,885
Scott: Yeah, the roux, right?

630
00:40:43,025 --> 00:40:48,780
Scott: And then you add the butter flour and then your spice, you know, whatever your curry spices are in with the butter flour.

631
00:40:48,800 --> 00:40:50,740
Rym: But what Scott just said, that's mistake number one.

632
00:40:50,880 --> 00:40:59,420
Rym: When you make a bad chili, a lot of times it's because you put the garlic or the spices in way too early when you're still cooking the base stuff and you burn and fuck up the spices and the garlic.

633
00:40:59,420 --> 00:41:02,568
Scott: But I was saying, that's the difference between curry and chili, right?

634
00:41:02,588 --> 00:41:05,496
Scott: So curry is like, you know, you got your water, right?

635
00:41:05,616 --> 00:41:06,839
Scott: And then you roux it up.

636
00:41:07,460 --> 00:41:11,875
Scott: With chili, it's like, you're not really putting too much water going on there.

637
00:41:11,895 --> 00:41:13,520
Scott: You're definitely not making a roux with butter.

638
00:41:13,860 --> 00:41:15,018
Scott: No, no, no, no.

639
00:41:15,180 --> 00:41:16,423
Scott: No, no, no, no, no, right?

640
00:41:16,463 --> 00:41:23,458
Scott: You're going with something tomato based maybe or, you know, some kind of, you know, maybe like some kind of stock or something, right?

641
00:41:24,160 --> 00:41:25,684
Rym: Recently, that's made my chili way better.

642
00:41:25,724 --> 00:41:31,160
Rym: Like recently, like in the past five or six years that when I was younger, I didn't understand it's made my chili so much better.

643
00:41:31,762 --> 00:41:35,160
Rym: I realized you don't add the tomato until way late in the process.

644
00:41:35,933 --> 00:41:36,140
Rym: Oh, yeah.

645
00:41:36,200 --> 00:41:40,472
Rym: The acid in the tomato kind of fucks it up and makes it harder to like make the meats.

646
00:41:40,592 --> 00:41:43,380
Rym: Like it causes all these chemistry problems in the chili.

647
00:41:45,061 --> 00:41:50,200
Rym: The other thing I learned to do better was instead of cooking the garlic, because I like to put a ton of garlic in.

648
00:41:50,840 --> 00:41:58,640
Rym: Instead of cooking it separately, what I do is after I've made the fond and I've got all the vegetables, I make a little hole in the middle of the fond and I put some oil in the middle of that hole.

649
00:41:59,040 --> 00:42:02,913
Rym: And I put all the garlic there and cook it by itself in the middle of the hole for like two minutes.

650
00:42:03,254 --> 00:42:04,940
Rym: Then I mix it all together and then I deglaze.

651
00:42:05,820 --> 00:42:06,461
Scott: Oh, you could do that.

652
00:42:06,481 --> 00:42:12,654
Scott: It really depends on if you're looking to keep the garlic in there.

653
00:42:12,715 --> 00:42:15,260
Scott: It's like you're maybe getting little niblets of garlic.

654
00:42:15,460 --> 00:42:17,980
Rym: Or do you want it to be a paste that just causes garlic flavor?

655
00:42:18,801 --> 00:42:19,782
Scott: You could do that too.

656
00:42:20,383 --> 00:42:30,040
Scott: Or you could just take a whole head of garlic, right, chop it in half down the middle, toss it in, skins and all, right, and then you just got to get it out.

657
00:42:30,586 --> 00:42:30,654
Scott: Yup.

658
00:42:30,860 --> 00:42:31,789
Scott: Before you serve it.

659
00:42:31,890 --> 00:42:32,738
Scott: And that'll really...

660
00:42:33,041 --> 00:42:34,140
Rym: Use it like you use a bay leaf.

661
00:42:34,841 --> 00:42:35,001
Scott: Right.

662
00:42:35,022 --> 00:42:38,300
Scott: You'll get a fucking ton of garlic flavor into that, you know, whatever you want.

663
00:42:38,320 --> 00:42:43,417
Rym: Though I'll admit I've found that if I want that kind of chili, using a bunch of granulated garlic has the exact same effect.

664
00:42:43,457 --> 00:42:44,340
Rym: You can't taste the difference.

665
00:42:44,881 --> 00:42:45,181
Scott: Yeah.

666
00:42:45,282 --> 00:42:49,674
Scott: But I'm saying like that's a, you know, usually I think the put the whole head of garlic in.

667
00:42:49,714 --> 00:42:51,498
Scott: You could do it with the chili.

668
00:42:51,519 --> 00:42:52,040
Scott: It'll be good.

669
00:42:52,223 --> 00:42:52,317
Scott: Yeah.

670
00:42:52,520 --> 00:42:54,645
Scott: But I think, you know, usually you're not.

671
00:42:55,247 --> 00:42:58,014
Scott: you're not pouring a chili through like a strainer, right?

672
00:42:58,576 --> 00:43:00,260
Scott: The way you would say making like a chicken soup.

673
00:43:00,300 --> 00:43:00,381
Rym: Yeah.

674
00:43:00,401 --> 00:43:01,569
Rym: You don't want to have to fish it all out.

675
00:43:01,589 --> 00:43:03,060
Rym: I've done that a couple times in my life.

676
00:43:03,260 --> 00:43:04,326
Scott: But you could, you know, but you can.

677
00:43:04,366 --> 00:43:06,760
Scott: You can put a little string on it and then you can get out.

678
00:43:07,220 --> 00:43:13,400
Rym: But for those of you who might not know a lot about like better cooking techniques, the fond, what we're talking about there.

679
00:43:13,601 --> 00:43:18,940
Rym: So imagine you have a bunch of celery or onions or stuff in the pot and you're cooking a whole bunch like over kind of high heat.

680
00:43:19,780 --> 00:43:23,180
Rym: This brown crust has formed inside of your entire pot now, like everywhere.

681
00:43:23,740 --> 00:43:25,240
Scott: Assuming you don't have some nonstick.

682
00:43:25,460 --> 00:43:25,902
Scott: Yeah.

683
00:43:26,203 --> 00:43:30,100
Rym: I don't think you can make a particularly good chili in a nonstick pan.

684
00:43:30,460 --> 00:43:31,380
Scott: I don't think you could either.

685
00:43:31,540 --> 00:43:32,343
Rym: Because you need that fond.

686
00:43:32,383 --> 00:43:33,327
Rym: The fond will form.

687
00:43:33,788 --> 00:43:36,960
Rym: Normally, like when I was younger, I always thought that was me fucking up and like cooking too hot.

688
00:43:37,061 --> 00:43:38,740
Rym: But then I learned the secret of deglazing.

689
00:43:39,202 --> 00:43:42,233
Scott: Right, so it's like the Maillard reaction happens.

690
00:43:42,314 --> 00:43:43,980
Scott: Like you put an onion in a pan, right?

691
00:43:44,320 --> 00:43:44,380
Scott: Yep.

692
00:43:44,401 --> 00:43:47,120
Scott: The onion starts to brown because of the Maillard reaction, right?

693
00:43:47,620 --> 00:43:48,648
Rym: That brown is not bad.

694
00:43:48,709 --> 00:43:50,100
Rym: That is pure flavor country.

695
00:43:50,520 --> 00:43:51,644
Scott: That is the delicious part.

696
00:43:51,744 --> 00:43:56,080
Scott: But some of that brown will just like come off the onion and be stuck to the pan.

697
00:43:56,200 --> 00:43:57,846
Scott: So it's like, OK, I got this piece of onion.

698
00:43:58,327 --> 00:44:00,073
Scott: It's grilled and heated nicely.

699
00:44:00,153 --> 00:44:02,140
Scott: So it's got, you know, browning and it tastes great.

700
00:44:02,622 --> 00:44:04,050
Scott: But some of the browning fell off.

701
00:44:04,633 --> 00:44:05,880
Scott: It's on the bottom of my pan.

702
00:44:06,180 --> 00:44:06,342
Rym: Yep.

703
00:44:06,604 --> 00:44:08,239
Scott: You got to scrape that shit up.

704
00:44:08,400 --> 00:44:10,324
Rym: And scraping it is real hard.

705
00:44:10,384 --> 00:44:11,667
Rym: That's why you deglaze.

706
00:44:11,787 --> 00:44:18,000
Rym: Use something like alcohol and you put a little bit of it in and it'll basically just melt all the fond into your food.

707
00:44:18,940 --> 00:44:19,061
Scott: Right.

708
00:44:19,081 --> 00:44:22,335
Scott: So, for example, a lot of, and this isn't just chili, a lot of food cooking.

709
00:44:22,476 --> 00:44:23,380
Scott: this happens in, right?

710
00:44:23,540 --> 00:44:23,661
Scott: Yep.

711
00:44:23,681 --> 00:44:24,828
Rym: Deglazing, like hook that up.

712
00:44:24,869 --> 00:44:26,660
Rym: And there's whole sets of instructions and techniques.

713
00:44:26,740 --> 00:44:32,336
Scott: A lot of times, you know, like I'll like take some chicken on the skinless thighs, right?

714
00:44:32,376 --> 00:44:33,239
Scott: With some olive oil.

715
00:44:33,499 --> 00:44:33,700
Scott: Right.

716
00:44:34,120 --> 00:44:35,304
Scott: They brown up nicely.

717
00:44:35,324 --> 00:44:40,600
Scott: And then it's like, OK, let's throw in all this other stuff and a splash of cooking wine.

718
00:44:40,700 --> 00:44:40,981
Rym: Yep.

719
00:44:41,483 --> 00:44:46,120
Rym: Or some vinegar or sherry or brandy works really well.

720
00:44:46,741 --> 00:44:46,983
Scott: Yeah.

721
00:44:47,103 --> 00:44:49,859
Scott: Or even sometimes, depending on what you got, water can do it too.

722
00:44:49,959 --> 00:44:50,120
Scott: Right.

723
00:44:50,500 --> 00:44:54,699
Scott: And suddenly all that stuff that was on the bottom of the pan comes right up and absorbs in.

724
00:44:55,621 --> 00:44:55,741
Scott: Right.

725
00:44:55,781 --> 00:44:56,302
Scott: And there you go.

726
00:44:56,362 --> 00:45:04,380
Scott: So you can even, for example, like say brown some chicken, take the chicken out of the, your chicken's done now, take it out and then make a sauce.

727
00:45:04,981 --> 00:45:08,780
Scott: And, you know, while you're making the sauce, all the stuff gets incorporated into the sauce.

728
00:45:09,041 --> 00:45:09,325
Rym: Yeah.

729
00:45:09,386 --> 00:45:10,240
Rym: I've done that a few times.

730
00:45:10,280 --> 00:45:15,520
Scott: And then you would pour that sauce over the chicken out of the pan and your pan should look clean, but you still need to clean it.

731
00:45:15,880 --> 00:45:29,980
Rym: For my basic chili, I usually use like a brown ale or a red ale, like a beer, and I'll basically pour half a can of beer into the fond and use that to deglaze because that adds a really nice flavor and all the alcohol obviously evaporates.

732
00:45:32,781 --> 00:45:41,658
Scott: Another thing you can do, right, is like a lot of people, I think, when they make chili, right, they're like, you know, you got to worry about the actual chilies, right?

733
00:45:42,018 --> 00:45:42,840
Scott: Where the name comes from.

734
00:45:42,960 --> 00:45:51,560
Rym: So I just use chili powder, but, or in the state after I get the onions and the celery down, then I'll do that again with a whole bunch of peppers that I've chopped up.

735
00:45:52,140 --> 00:45:52,240
Scott: Right.

736
00:45:52,280 --> 00:45:58,088
Scott: But I think the real pro technique is to get dried chilies, right?

737
00:45:58,148 --> 00:46:06,980
Scott: Because the dried chilies, if you're not growing, if you're not growing your own, if you're looking at dried chilies, there are so many more available varieties.

738
00:46:07,281 --> 00:46:08,062
Rym: Yep.

739
00:46:08,163 --> 00:46:10,047
Scott: Especially if you live in like a city, right?

740
00:46:10,087 --> 00:46:15,200
Scott: Like I could go to the Mexican grocery and get a shit ton of different chilies, all crazy kinds, but they're all dried.

741
00:46:15,540 --> 00:46:15,660
Scott: Yep.

742
00:46:15,680 --> 00:46:15,841
Scott: Right?

743
00:46:16,562 --> 00:46:19,909
Scott: So you can rehydrate them, which is totally easy to do, right?

744
00:46:20,771 --> 00:46:25,240
Scott: You can get fresh chilies and like roast them down a little bit on a sheet pan in the oven.

745
00:46:25,540 --> 00:46:25,741
Scott: Yep.

746
00:46:25,881 --> 00:46:26,081
Scott: Right?

747
00:46:26,182 --> 00:46:33,260
Rym: Especially, don't use poblanos in particular, roast them first because they will not break down fast enough if you cook them in the pot by themselves, the skins thick.

748
00:46:33,941 --> 00:46:36,700
Scott: The other thing, well, yeah, well, you roast them and you could take the skins off.

749
00:46:37,260 --> 00:46:37,360
Rym: Yep.

750
00:46:37,441 --> 00:46:37,822
Rym: Exactly.

751
00:46:37,842 --> 00:46:39,248
Rym: There's a whole technique about that.

752
00:46:39,389 --> 00:46:40,071
Rym: It's like, look it up.

753
00:46:40,111 --> 00:46:42,200
Rym: It's a crazy technique with plastic bags, but it works.

754
00:46:42,700 --> 00:46:42,964
Scott: I don't know.

755
00:46:43,004 --> 00:46:44,139
Scott: You don't always need a plastic bag.

756
00:46:44,400 --> 00:46:46,493
Rym: The plastic bag just works so well.

757
00:46:46,553 --> 00:46:47,700
Rym: It's so easy once you learn it.

758
00:46:48,560 --> 00:46:50,180
Scott: You cook things to get the skins to peel off.

759
00:46:50,260 --> 00:46:52,047
Rym: Yeah, but it depends on the pepper too.

760
00:46:52,087 --> 00:46:53,955
Rym: Like a lot of the peppers I use, you don't need to do this.

761
00:46:53,995 --> 00:46:55,260
Rym: You can just cook the whole pepper chopped up.

762
00:46:55,660 --> 00:47:01,160
Scott: But the other thing you can do is you can take those, right, and throw them in if you've got a blender or a food processor.

763
00:47:01,460 --> 00:47:01,781
Rym: Yep.

764
00:47:01,981 --> 00:47:02,262
Rym: Right?

765
00:47:02,662 --> 00:47:13,200
Scott: So you get all your actual, you know, chilies, right, blend it up real good that way, and then they go in with all your meats into your stew pot.

766
00:47:13,540 --> 00:47:13,701
Rym: Yep.

767
00:47:13,721 --> 00:47:19,000
Scott: So after that, after you get the meat- If you just throw a bunch of chilies in a pot, that's not going to work out as well.

768
00:47:19,260 --> 00:47:20,182
Rym: So I have to get the meat in.

769
00:47:20,202 --> 00:47:22,769
Rym: I let it cook for like an hour, maybe longer.

770
00:47:22,869 --> 00:47:25,195
Rym: Like, chili just gets better the longer you let it cook.

771
00:47:25,275 --> 00:47:27,100
Rym: Like, that's just, that's the magic of chili.

772
00:47:27,641 --> 00:47:28,965
Scott: It depends on certain things, right?

773
00:47:29,005 --> 00:47:34,780
Scott: So if, you know, you've, you know, you might want to like, you know, say you're going real fancy, you want to do more like a barbecue chili.

774
00:47:35,801 --> 00:47:35,981
Scott: Right?

775
00:47:36,001 --> 00:47:44,080
Scott: So you can use that long chili cooking time as like a slow cooking for the meat to get it to be, you know, very barbecue tender, fall apart.

776
00:47:44,700 --> 00:47:44,860
Scott: Right?

777
00:47:44,881 --> 00:47:46,264
Scott: Like a pulled pork situation.

778
00:47:46,885 --> 00:47:53,060
Scott: But maybe if you've, you know, got like a ground beef and you browned it already, you don't need as long a cook time there.

779
00:47:53,240 --> 00:47:53,942
Scott: Right.

780
00:47:54,343 --> 00:48:01,580
Rym: But after all that cooking, then is when I add the tomato and if there's beans or tofu or anything, I put all that stuff in.

781
00:48:01,780 --> 00:48:03,046
Rym: Like, so it's cooked for an hour.

782
00:48:03,127 --> 00:48:05,760
Rym: Then I put all the tomato and everything in for like 10 more minutes of cooking.

783
00:48:06,980 --> 00:48:08,954
Scott: Because the thing about eating the chili, right?

784
00:48:08,994 --> 00:48:09,800
Scott: The most important part.

785
00:48:09,940 --> 00:48:10,101
Scott: Yep.

786
00:48:10,201 --> 00:48:10,402
Scott: Right.

787
00:48:10,724 --> 00:48:12,753
Scott: Is you could just put it in a bowl and eat it with a spoon.

788
00:48:12,994 --> 00:48:14,280
Scott: Isn't that, that's perfectly acceptable.

789
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:17,953
Rym: My go-to is put it over rice or have croutons on top.

790
00:48:18,254 --> 00:48:19,520
Rym: Those are my two main ways.

791
00:48:19,981 --> 00:48:26,340
Scott: I feel like you have to add some kind of bread, rice, grain thing.

792
00:48:26,900 --> 00:48:28,290
Rym: It just makes it a complete meal.

793
00:48:28,391 --> 00:48:29,560
Rym: It tastes, it feels right.

794
00:48:30,380 --> 00:48:37,536
Scott: But I never want that grain to be a, uh, if the chili is next to the grain, right?

795
00:48:37,917 --> 00:48:39,340
Scott: Then the grain could be special.

796
00:48:39,480 --> 00:48:42,831
Scott: So for example, I could have a bowl of chili with a garlic bread next to it.

797
00:48:42,952 --> 00:48:45,420
Scott: I could have a bowl of chili with a cornbread next to it.

798
00:48:45,420 --> 00:48:48,320
Rym: But if it's chili in a bread bowl, that's just gotta be some plain ass bread.

799
00:48:48,500 --> 00:48:48,962
Rym: That's right.

800
00:48:49,062 --> 00:49:06,060
Scott: If the chili is touching the bread or the rice or the grain, right, in any way, top or bottom, side, then that bread has to be plain as hell because it is just a bread vehicle, a wheat train, right, with meat passengers.

801
00:49:06,460 --> 00:49:12,420
Rym: Chili in a bread bowl is like literally like one of my top 10 favorite foods on earth.

802
00:49:12,940 --> 00:49:17,700
Scott: It is an extremely convenient way to eat chili because you don't have to think about the bread part or the bowl part.

803
00:49:17,740 --> 00:49:22,534
Rym: Every time I ski, ski resorts are famous for having fucking garbage food.

804
00:49:23,055 --> 00:49:24,720
Rym: Even fancy ski resorts, the food is just garbage.

805
00:49:24,780 --> 00:49:27,780
Scott: Oh, but they're also famous for having warm food because people are fucking cold.

806
00:49:28,120 --> 00:49:32,900
Rym: Yup, but every ski resort, even the shittiest one, has fantastic chili.

807
00:49:34,380 --> 00:49:37,940
Scott: Yeah, even someone who's not a great chef can make a chili.

808
00:49:38,340 --> 00:49:38,400
Scott: Yup.

809
00:49:38,862 --> 00:49:50,964
Rym: My dad was a fireman and part of the reason I was so obsessed with chili is because we ate chili a lot because firemen in firehouses, like they'll go on rotation for like a week at a time, they all take turns cooking because they're living in the firehouse, they make chili like 80%

810
00:49:50,964 --> 00:49:51,406
Scott: of the time.

811
00:49:51,426 --> 00:49:53,777
Scott: Chili is like the stereotypical fireman, right?

812
00:49:54,520 --> 00:49:57,332
Rym: Like firehouse chili is a thing, like that's a kind of chili.

813
00:49:58,216 --> 00:49:59,260
Rym: Put some cayenne pepper in it.

814
00:49:59,500 --> 00:50:02,820
Scott: And they'll even say things like, you know, five alarm chili, right?

815
00:50:03,521 --> 00:50:03,682
Scott: Yup.

816
00:50:03,922 --> 00:50:08,700
Scott: Or, you know, I can't think of a single firehouse on earth that doesn't have their own chili cook-off.

817
00:50:08,880 --> 00:50:09,967
Rym: Oh, 100% and their own chili recipe.

818
00:50:09,987 --> 00:50:12,180
Scott: I've never heard of one, at least in the United States.

819
00:50:12,441 --> 00:50:22,800
Rym: And because I ended up, because my dad was a lieutenant and he ended up being like the deputy chief, so as a kid and growing up, I met a lot of like, I went to a lot of different like firehouses over the course of my life.

820
00:50:23,100 --> 00:50:29,260
Rym: And the one thing I remember is that every one of them had the one guy who made the chili for that firehouse because he was the best.

821
00:50:30,460 --> 00:50:31,413
Rym: Like everyone had like one guy.

822
00:50:32,500 --> 00:50:35,820
Scott: That's the guy who's entering the competition at the end of the year against the other firehouses.

823
00:50:36,640 --> 00:50:40,880
Rym: My memory may be a little faulty, but I'm pretty sure 100% of the chili guys had full mustaches.

824
00:50:41,583 --> 00:50:41,823
Scott: Oh yeah.

825
00:50:41,984 --> 00:50:43,088
Scott: I mean, you can't make a chili.

826
00:50:43,148 --> 00:50:46,260
Scott: You gotta grow the mustache first before you can make the chili or else it'll turn out like shit.

827
00:50:46,480 --> 00:50:46,621
Scott: Yup.

828
00:50:46,742 --> 00:50:48,594
Rym: My chili got worse when I shaved off the mustache.

829
00:50:48,634 --> 00:50:49,560
Rym: That's one problem.

830
00:50:50,280 --> 00:50:50,600
Rym: That's right.

831
00:50:50,920 --> 00:50:56,080
Rym: The other important component of eating the chili, not always, but for most chilis, I want to have a cold thing.

832
00:50:56,320 --> 00:51:00,859
Rym: Either a sour cream or a cheese to mix into it.

833
00:51:01,921 --> 00:51:07,899
Rym: Well, okay, so mixing in I'm not too big on because that can dilute- Well, you put it on top and I only mix it in right as I'm eating it.

834
00:51:08,581 --> 00:51:08,701
Scott: Right.

835
00:51:08,741 --> 00:51:10,505
Scott: That can dilute the power of the chili.

836
00:51:10,565 --> 00:51:18,540
Scott: If I do a sour cream, then what I want to do is I want to sort of like, you know, get a little chili on a bread and then put a sour cream and then eat that.

837
00:51:18,600 --> 00:51:18,942
Rym: Oh yeah.

838
00:51:19,023 --> 00:51:21,800
Rym: I like to put a blob of sour cream on top of the chili bowl.

839
00:51:21,800 --> 00:51:29,260
Scott: I'll even do that just like in the house, not even chili, but like if I'm eating chips and salsa, I'll just get sour cream and I'll dip the chip in the salsa and then in the sour cream.

840
00:51:29,720 --> 00:51:29,785
Scott: Yup.

841
00:51:30,400 --> 00:51:35,836
Scott: But I think if you're doing cheese or any kind of dairy, I just get the bowl of chili ready.

842
00:51:35,856 --> 00:51:37,040
Scott: So if we're doing the bread bowl, right?

843
00:51:37,181 --> 00:51:39,960
Rym: If you sprinkle it on the top, make a layer like a French onion soup.

844
00:51:40,360 --> 00:51:41,603
Scott: Top, top sprinkle, right?

845
00:51:41,623 --> 00:51:46,556
Scott: I get the cheese grater, I get the block of cheese and then I go right on top of the bowl, right?

846
00:51:46,616 --> 00:51:47,399
Scott: No mixing, right?

847
00:51:48,400 --> 00:51:49,650
Rym: And I don't use a fancy cheese.

848
00:51:49,771 --> 00:51:50,880
Rym: I use like Monterey Jack or cheddar.

849
00:51:51,020 --> 00:51:51,562
Scott: Oh, no, no, no.

850
00:51:51,642 --> 00:51:56,580
Scott: I use the regular old just cheddar cheese, you know, rectangle from the grocery store.

851
00:51:56,840 --> 00:51:57,840
Rym: Monterey Jack is a good choice.

852
00:51:58,162 --> 00:51:59,639
Scott: It could be a sharp one, but you know.

853
00:51:59,760 --> 00:52:10,540
Rym: But if your chili is particularly powerful or good on its own and you don't want to even like compromise at all, you just want that cheese like texture and flavor, Monterey Jack is not a bad way to go on a chili.

854
00:52:10,800 --> 00:52:10,941
Rym: No, no.

855
00:52:11,303 --> 00:52:14,320
Scott: I think, you know, nothing fancier than Laughing Cow should be going on.

856
00:52:14,520 --> 00:52:14,570
Scott: No.

857
00:52:16,663 --> 00:52:20,920
Scott: And I think most of the Laughing Cow varieties aren't even chili appropriate, I don't think.

858
00:52:21,641 --> 00:52:32,960
Rym: So in terms of the other bits of chili, and I think we've gone on for long enough about chili, when I cook it, I usually use a beef broth instead of water because that just makes the chili way more flavorful without me having to fuck with it.

859
00:52:34,260 --> 00:52:35,121
Rym: Like that works pretty well.

860
00:52:35,402 --> 00:52:46,580
Rym: Sometimes I'll make, but if I don't want to mess up the flavor, I'll use a vegetarian broth or I'll just use water and add enough salt to the water to make it as salty as broth, but to not add any flavor.

861
00:52:47,261 --> 00:52:48,685
Scott: Yeah, I'm still not an expert on this.

862
00:52:48,746 --> 00:52:55,240
Rym: I know that stock comes from like, you know, bones and broth comes from- We made some the other night, I can show you how to make broth.

863
00:52:56,040 --> 00:52:58,024
Scott: No, no, no, but I'm saying is like, you know, it's like.

864
00:52:58,044 --> 00:53:00,369
Scott: I know this stock versus broth, right?

865
00:53:00,550 --> 00:53:04,117
Scott: But it's like when would you, you know, when do you use one and when the other?

866
00:53:04,178 --> 00:53:05,260
Scott: Or is stock just better?

867
00:53:05,520 --> 00:53:07,947
Rym: You know what, in terms of chili, I found it doesn't matter.

868
00:53:08,128 --> 00:53:11,939
Rym: I've used all different kinds of stocks and broths and like even my saltwater technique.

869
00:53:12,120 --> 00:53:24,658
Scott: Because I get the feeling that like, you know, when I hear like chefs, I've never heard them say it directly, but I get the feeling whenever I watch cooking programs that stock is just better than broth, fuck broth, right?

870
00:53:24,678 --> 00:53:25,760
Scott: That's like the vibe I get.

871
00:53:25,960 --> 00:53:26,803
Rym: All right, I just googled it.

872
00:53:26,843 --> 00:53:28,347
Rym: What's the difference between stock and broth?

873
00:53:28,548 --> 00:53:32,880
Rym: The terms stock and broth are used interchangeably and you can substitute one for the other within recipes.

874
00:53:33,644 --> 00:53:34,018
Scott: Uh-huh.

875
00:53:34,160 --> 00:53:36,679
Rym: There's slight difference in their preparation, like that's it.

876
00:53:37,521 --> 00:53:45,975
Scott: All right, well, anyway, if you go to the grocery store, you'll definitely see the same brand selling in a carton, right?

877
00:53:46,235 --> 00:53:49,080
Scott: Stock and broth of the same animal and they're two different products.

878
00:53:50,040 --> 00:53:54,900
Rym: But seriously, like you can get away with just water and salt if you put enough good ingredients in there.

879
00:53:55,400 --> 00:54:03,900
Rym: And in terms of tomato, I either use fresh crushed tomatoes, like from a, not fresh, but like from a can, but like crushed or diced or honestly.

880
00:54:04,861 --> 00:54:10,080
Scott: If you got tomato, can is the way to go unless it's that one moment of the year where tomato is in season.

881
00:54:10,581 --> 00:54:10,882
Rym: Yup.

882
00:54:10,902 --> 00:54:14,155
Rym: Tomato paste, however, you can't tell the difference.

883
00:54:14,175 --> 00:54:15,360
Rym: Tomato paste, like if you're chili.

884
00:54:15,660 --> 00:54:16,620
Scott: Tomato paste is from a can.

885
00:54:17,140 --> 00:54:23,655
Rym: Yeah, but tomato paste is fine compared to like a big thing of diced tomatoes and way easier to work with and you can store it longer.

886
00:54:23,796 --> 00:54:25,620
Rym: and tomato paste is just like magic.

887
00:54:25,960 --> 00:54:33,320
Rym: If a chili doesn't feel quite right, or you kind of messed up the flavor profile, more tomato will just make it taste more like generic chili and save you.

888
00:54:33,662 --> 00:54:35,760
Rym: Tomato paste is like tomato concentrate.

889
00:54:36,640 --> 00:54:38,827
Scott: Yeah, I mean tomato paste is literally tomato concentrate.

890
00:54:38,907 --> 00:54:42,880
Scott: If you need tomato sauce, just take tomato paste and water and look, you got tomato sauce.

891
00:54:43,100 --> 00:54:43,175
Scott: Yup.

892
00:54:43,603 --> 00:54:44,279
Scott: That's how it works.

893
00:54:44,520 --> 00:54:44,616
Scott: Yup.

894
00:54:44,740 --> 00:54:45,300
Scott: That's the point.

895
00:54:45,640 --> 00:54:52,194
Rym: In terms of the spices, I tend to, the one thing I really don't deviate from is I tend to mostly just use chili powder.

896
00:54:52,595 --> 00:54:53,857
Rym: A shit ton of cumin.

897
00:54:53,877 --> 00:54:55,180
Rym: I love cumin.

898
00:54:55,841 --> 00:54:56,122
Scott: Oh yeah.

899
00:54:56,403 --> 00:55:02,957
Scott: We got, Amanda was making a chili today and she's like, "I bought this giant cumin, but look, it's running out.

900
00:55:03,017 --> 00:55:03,678
Scott: I make so much

901
00:55:03,698 --> 00:55:03,919
Scott: chili.".

902
00:55:04,500 --> 00:55:10,157
Scott: It's like, we never buy big things because there's not a lot of people and we don't eat that much food in New York.

903
00:55:10,177 --> 00:55:11,360
Scott: You don't have a lot of storage space.

904
00:55:11,440 --> 00:55:14,420
Scott: We don't like to buy big, you know, we like to buy small amounts.

905
00:55:14,560 --> 00:55:15,959
Rym: Only now am I buying big things.

906
00:55:16,780 --> 00:55:18,930
Scott: Right, but she's like, "I bought this big cumin,".

907
00:55:19,131 --> 00:55:20,638
Scott: and it's like, "I never want to buy a big

908
00:55:20,698 --> 00:55:20,939
Scott: thing.".

909
00:55:21,283 --> 00:55:21,916
Rym: Cumin's so good.

910
00:55:22,361 --> 00:55:25,557
Rym: Like, however much cumin you think you should use in a chili, just use three times as much.

911
00:55:25,577 --> 00:55:26,140
Rym: It'll be fine.

912
00:55:26,700 --> 00:55:26,800
Scott: Right.

913
00:55:26,821 --> 00:55:30,740
Scott: We use so much cumin in the chili that the big one was the right purchase.

914
00:55:31,040 --> 00:55:31,180
Rym: Yup.

915
00:55:31,220 --> 00:55:38,598
Rym: And then I either use smoked paprika or cayenne pepper, depending on what kind of kick I want to give it and all the rest of the flavor.

916
00:55:38,618 --> 00:55:39,560
Rym: I just want it to come from my ingredients.

917
00:55:39,580 --> 00:55:40,479
Scott: Yeah, they're pretty similar-ish.

918
00:55:40,940 --> 00:55:41,020
Rym: Yeah.

919
00:55:41,804 --> 00:55:44,920
Rym: Mostly depends if I want it smokier versus, like, spicier.

920
00:55:45,721 --> 00:55:51,332
Scott: Yeah, I think that's the thing is you got to mix, you know, the great chilies, you're mixing together different chili flavors.

921
00:55:51,352 --> 00:55:55,060
Scott: You get, like, a fruity pepper and a spicy pepper and a smoky pepper.

922
00:55:55,600 --> 00:55:58,260
Scott: Get all three or balance them in some way.

923
00:55:58,520 --> 00:56:02,560
Rym: Or don't balance them and lean in heavily to one and make a very, like, specific kind of chili.

924
00:56:03,840 --> 00:56:09,017
Rym: Habaneros are real good for flavor, but do not try to make a chili with just habaneros.

925
00:56:09,037 --> 00:56:09,760
Rym: You'll be in for a bad time.

926
00:56:10,041 --> 00:56:15,200
Scott: Whichever one of the peppers you lean into, the rest of the chili has to sort of contrast.

927
00:56:16,180 --> 00:56:16,421
Scott: Right?

928
00:56:16,561 --> 00:56:23,160
Scott: So if you got, say, you know, if you go in, like, the extra, like, on fire spice, like a real tangy kind of spice.

929
00:56:23,220 --> 00:56:25,219
Rym: Don't also go heavy on chipotle in that.

930
00:56:25,920 --> 00:56:26,161
Scott: Right.

931
00:56:26,221 --> 00:56:31,620
Scott: Then you might want to come back on it and go maybe more, you know, with some dairy on that, right?

932
00:56:31,861 --> 00:56:36,216
Scott: Or, you know, maybe a sweeter tomato to go on the other side.

933
00:56:37,460 --> 00:56:45,600
Rym: Like, one thing I really like to make is instead of using a lot of chili powder, I'll get, like, three or four pounds of rainbow peppers, just, like, random sweet peppers.

934
00:56:46,040 --> 00:56:51,120
Rym: Chop them all up and I'll braise those down just like I would with the celery and the onion.

935
00:56:51,801 --> 00:56:54,814
Rym: And then for a kick, I just add a bunch of cayenne pepper.

936
00:56:55,176 --> 00:56:56,020
Rym: That works real well.

937
00:56:56,762 --> 00:56:58,080
Rym: And it makes, like, almost a sweet chili.

938
00:56:59,300 --> 00:57:00,911
Rym: So you get this contrasting sweet and spicy.

939
00:57:02,641 --> 00:57:03,280
Rym: Last thing about chili?

940
00:57:04,140 --> 00:57:05,619
Scott: Yeah, because we got to end the show.

941
00:57:05,762 --> 00:57:06,900
Rym: Yep, and I'm getting hungry, so.

942
00:57:07,360 --> 00:57:08,719
Scott: Is that, oh, well, you've been talking about chili.

943
00:57:08,920 --> 00:57:09,872
Rym: I know, I'm getting real hungry.

944
00:57:09,892 --> 00:57:10,480
Rym: I want some chili.

945
00:57:11,202 --> 00:57:11,860
Scott: I ate food already.

946
00:57:12,040 --> 00:57:13,579
Rym: I think we're going to get a Baroness burger tonight.

947
00:57:14,300 --> 00:57:14,720
Scott: Ooh, exciting.

948
00:57:15,621 --> 00:57:19,860
Scott: Is that, unlike a lot of other foods, chili is good all times.

949
00:57:20,180 --> 00:57:22,314
Rym: Oh, yeah, breakfast chili, Bob, chili omelet.

950
00:57:24,641 --> 00:57:27,800
Scott: Breakfast chili, lunch chili, dinner chili, all appropriate.

951
00:57:27,840 --> 00:57:29,859
Rym: Late night snack chili, you'll get heartburn, but fuck it.

952
00:57:30,681 --> 00:57:30,902
Scott: Right.

953
00:57:31,145 --> 00:57:32,940
Scott: And then, not only that, but all seasons.

954
00:57:33,182 --> 00:57:35,500
Scott: Summer chili, winter chili, right?

955
00:57:35,661 --> 00:57:36,026
Scott: I'm cold.

956
00:57:36,127 --> 00:57:36,979
Scott: I want to eat warm chili.

957
00:57:37,360 --> 00:57:37,845
Scott: It's summer.

958
00:57:37,946 --> 00:57:39,540
Scott: Let's go outside and have a chili cook-off.

959
00:57:39,660 --> 00:57:41,860
Scott: And also, I have chili at the barbecue.

960
00:57:41,960 --> 00:57:42,438
Scott: Made too much?

961
00:57:42,720 --> 00:57:43,627
Scott: I'll have a chili dog.

962
00:57:43,667 --> 00:57:45,400
Scott: I'll dip my hot dogs in the chili in the summer.

963
00:57:45,460 --> 00:57:47,080
Rym: But in the middle of winter, cooking some chili?

964
00:57:47,300 --> 00:57:49,080
Rym: All right, now there's a bunch of humidity in the apartment.

965
00:57:49,441 --> 00:57:50,279
Rym: Everything smells good.

966
00:57:50,700 --> 00:57:51,919
Scott: Oh, it's dry because the heat's on.

967
00:57:52,220 --> 00:57:52,341
Rym: Yep.

968
00:57:53,230 --> 00:57:54,320
Rym: But you make humidity.

969
00:57:55,060 --> 00:57:55,221
Scott: Right.

970
00:57:55,281 --> 00:58:03,820
Scott: There's never a time where it's not chili season, because everything you're using in the chili is meat, which it doesn't have a season, right?

971
00:58:04,460 --> 00:58:11,640
Scott: And canned vegetables and dried peppers and all these, you know, beans from a can, right?

972
00:58:11,741 --> 00:58:13,420
Scott: All the ingredients going in the chili.

973
00:58:14,121 --> 00:58:16,580
Scott: So, almost none of them are fresh and seasonal.

974
00:58:16,820 --> 00:58:19,380
Scott: All dried, preserved meats.

975
00:58:20,020 --> 00:58:21,680
Rym: Like onions and celery in particular.

976
00:58:21,961 --> 00:58:23,920
Rym: It does not have to be good onions or good celery.

977
00:58:24,261 --> 00:58:27,300
Rym: Usually, when I use celery, it's because we have too much celery.

978
00:58:27,460 --> 00:58:31,360
Scott: You can always get a good onion anytime if you live in a place that has food.

979
00:58:31,467 --> 00:58:31,597
Scott: Yep.

980
00:58:33,082 --> 00:58:35,340
Scott: So, that's one of the greatest things about chili.

981
00:58:35,600 --> 00:58:40,740
Scott: That even other, better, not to say chili is the greatest food on Earth, you know, it's a great food for sure.

982
00:58:40,820 --> 00:58:40,941
Rym: Yep.

983
00:58:41,042 --> 00:58:41,951
Rym: It's not my number one.

984
00:58:41,991 --> 00:58:42,859
Rym: It's just in my top ten.

985
00:58:43,220 --> 00:58:43,260
Scott: No.

986
00:58:43,280 --> 00:58:48,720
Scott: But it's like other, greater foods are often seasonal in some way or time-based, right?

987
00:58:48,820 --> 00:58:51,580
Scott: I wouldn't eat the delicious steak dinner for breakfast.

988
00:58:52,020 --> 00:58:52,528
Rym: Yep.

989
00:58:52,670 --> 00:58:53,340
Rym: Don't steak and eggs.

990
00:58:53,680 --> 00:58:55,520
Scott: But you don't- You could have a country fried steak for breakfast.

991
00:58:55,680 --> 00:58:55,801
Rym: Yep.

992
00:58:55,821 --> 00:58:58,920
Rym: But if you make steak and eggs, you're not making a filet mignon steak and eggs.

993
00:58:59,540 --> 00:58:59,961
Scott: Exactly.

994
00:59:00,222 --> 00:59:05,420
Scott: But chili is appropriate at per every meal, in every season, in every time, in every place.

995
00:59:05,520 --> 00:59:09,988
Rym: The other main property of chili, the last one that's real important that you didn't touch on- The real last one?

996
00:59:10,009 --> 00:59:10,720
Scott: I already did the last one.

997
00:59:10,720 --> 00:59:11,679
Rym: There is a last, last one.

998
00:59:12,060 --> 00:59:16,860
Rym: You're coming over the last, last- It's impossible to make too much because you can just freeze it and thaw it.

999
00:59:17,500 --> 00:59:19,800
Rym: Frozen chili, recooked, just tastes better.

1000
00:59:20,580 --> 00:59:20,721
Scott: Yeah.

1001
00:59:20,882 --> 00:59:22,694
Scott: I mean, you know, it's made of preserved stuff.

1002
00:59:22,754 --> 00:59:23,580
Scott: Just preserve it again.

1003
00:59:23,881 --> 00:59:33,460
Rym: And as long as you're careful with the temperatures and, like, If you freeze chili that you made, thaw it and cook a bunch of it, don't finish it, you can just refreeze that shit and it's good again.

1004
00:59:34,220 --> 00:59:34,423
Scott: Yeah.

1005
00:59:34,484 --> 00:59:35,599
Scott: No, it's not- What's wrong with it?

1006
00:59:35,860 --> 00:59:35,960
Rym: Yeah.

1007
00:59:36,001 --> 00:59:41,820
Rym: The only problem you can have is if you don't do right food safety and let it sit out too long because you'll slowly increase the bacterial load.

1008
00:59:41,860 --> 00:59:47,360
Scott: If you leave it in the fridge too long or you let it sit out too long, it's okay until you see something growing on it.

1009
00:59:47,460 --> 00:59:47,643
Rym: Yep.

1010
00:59:47,928 --> 00:59:48,640
Rym: So here's the secret.

1011
00:59:49,101 --> 00:59:53,440
Rym: If you make a lot of chili and you want to freeze it or get into your fridge, don't just put it in the freezer.

1012
